    <!-- Planned Permanence Essay - Expandable -->
    <section class="section" style="padding: 0;">
        <div class="obsolescence-block" onclick="toggleObsolescenceDetails()" id="obsolescenceBlock">
            <div class="obsolescence-header">
                <h2 class="gradient-text">Against Planned Obsolescence</h2>
                <p>A Philosophy of Permanence in Electronic Design</p>
                <span class="expand-icon" id="obsolescenceExpandIcon">⊕</span>
            </div>
            
            <div class="obsolescence-content" id="obsolescenceDetails">
                <div class="obsolescence-inner">
                    <div style="margin-bottom: 2rem; padding: 2rem; background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05); border-radius: 12px; border-left: 4px solid #4a9eff;">
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #4a9eff; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The Problem with Planned Obsolescence</p>
                        <p>In an era where electronic devices are designed to fail after warranty periods expire, where software updates deliberately slow older hardware, and where repair is made impossible through proprietary screws and serialized components, the LT4363-1 CAN protection circuit stands as a testament to a different philosophy: <strong style="color: #00d4ff;">Planned Permanence</strong>.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Planned obsolescence has become the dark undercurrent of modern electronics. Manufacturers deliberately design products with:</p>
                    
                    <ul style="list-style: none; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
                        <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                            <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #ff4444;">✗</span>
                            <strong>Artificial lifespans</strong> - Capacitors rated just beyond warranty periods
                        </li>
                        <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                            <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #ff4444;">✗</span>
                            <strong>Non-replaceable components</strong> - Soldered batteries and glued assemblies
                        </li>
                        <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                            <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #ff4444;">✗</span>
                            <strong>Proprietary interfaces</strong> - Preventing third-party repair or upgrades
                        </li>
                        <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                            <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #ff4444;">✗</span>
                            <strong>Software time bombs</strong> - Updates that cripple older hardware
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div style="margin: 3rem 0; padding: 2rem; background: rgba(74, 158, 255, 0.1); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid rgba(74, 158, 255, 0.3);">
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #4a9eff; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The LT4363-1 Design Philosophy</p>
                        <p>This protection circuit embodies <strong style="color: #00d4ff;">Planned Permanence</strong> through deliberate engineering choices:</p>
                        
                        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-top: 1.5rem;">
                            <div style="padding: 1rem; background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05); border-radius: 8px;">
                                <h4 style="color: #4a9eff; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Over-Specified Components</h4>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.95rem;">Every component is rated far beyond expected stress levels. The 55V tolerance protects 5V systems with 10x margin.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="padding: 1rem; background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05); border-radius: 8px;">
                                <h4 style="color: #4a9eff; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Standard Parts</h4>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.95rem;">Uses industry-standard components available from multiple manufacturers, ensuring long-term availability.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="padding: 1rem; background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05); border-radius: 8px;">
                                <h4 style="color: #4a9eff; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Repairable Design</h4>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.95rem;">Through-hole and large SMD components enable field repair with basic tools, not microscopes.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="padding: 1rem; background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05); border-radius: 8px;">
                                <h4 style="color: #4a9eff; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Open Documentation</h4>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.95rem;">Complete schematics and theory of operation ensure anyone can understand and maintain the circuit.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin: 3rem 0; padding: 2rem; background: rgba(0, 212, 255, 0.1); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid rgba(0, 212, 255, 0.3);">
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3rem; color: #00d4ff; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1rem; text-align: center;">The Environmental Imperative</p>
                        <p style="text-align: center;">Every device that lasts 20 years instead of 2 represents a <strong>90% reduction</strong> in manufacturing impact, e-waste, and resource consumption. Planned Permanence isn't just good engineering—it's environmental responsibility.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin: 3rem 0; padding: 2rem; background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.03); border-radius: 12px;">
                        <p style="font-size: 1.15rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Consider the stark contrast: While consumer electronics are designed to drive replacement cycles every 2-3 years, this protection circuit is engineered to outlive the vehicles and equipment it protects. The <strong style="color: #00d4ff;">500,000+ hour MTBF</strong> isn't marketing hyperbole—it's the result of:</p>
                        
                        <ul style="list-style: none; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                                <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #4a9eff;">✓</span>
                                <strong>Automotive-grade components</strong> rated for -40°C to +125°C operation
                            </li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                                <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #4a9eff;">✓</span>
                                <strong>Ceramic capacitors</strong> instead of electrolytics that dry out
                            </li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                                <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #4a9eff;">✓</span>
                                <strong>Metal film resistors</strong> with 1% tolerance that won't drift
                            </li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative;">
                                <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #4a9eff;">✓</span>
                                <strong>Solid-state design</strong> with no mechanical wear points
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        
                        <p style="font-size: 1.1rem;">This circuit will protect CAN networks in vehicles manufactured today that will still be on the road in 2050. It will safeguard industrial equipment that runs three shifts for decades. It will ensure reliable communication in infrastructure that our children will inherit.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #4a9eff; text-align: center; margin-top: 3rem; padding: 2rem; background: rgba(74, 158, 255, 0.1); border-radius: 12px;">
                        <strong>In a world racing toward disposability, permanence is revolutionary.</strong>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Technical Overview -->
    <section id="technical" class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title gradient-text">Technical Deep Dive</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">Understanding the LT4363-1 CAN_L Protection Architecture</p>
        
        <div class="tech-grid">
            <div class="tech-card">
                <h3>Core Specifications</h3>
                <ul class="tech-specs">
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Input Voltage Range</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">0-55V</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Normal CAN_L Range</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">0-3V</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Trip Voltage</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">10.3V</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Current Limit</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">100mA</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Response Time</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">1-10ms</span>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tech-card">
                <h3>Protection Features</h3>
                <ul class="tech-specs">
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">ESD Protection</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">23kV</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">EMI Filtering</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">120Ω@100MHz</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Transient Clamp</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">6.8V TVS</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">Temperature Range</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">-40°C to +125°C</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="spec-label">MTBF</span>
                        <span class="spec-value">>500,000 hrs</span>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tech-card">
                <h3>Circuit Intelligence</h3>
                <p style="line-height: 1.8;">The LT4363-1 continuously monitors voltage and current conditions, providing intelligent disconnect during fault events. The precision voltage divider (R1/R2) sets the exact trip point at 10.3V, optimized for 5V CAN systems while allowing normal CAN_L signal swing.</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #4a9eff; font-weight: 600;">V_trip = 1.275V × (1 + 16kΩ/2.2kΩ) = 10.3V</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: #888;">Note: The circuit includes a status LED for visual fault indication - a diagnostic feature that aids in troubleshooting.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

